
ILP for Enigma
knight (2010, then again in 2024)

y4.py creates y4.ilp, an integer linear program (ILP) that captures the workings of 
a "demo" Enigma machine with a 4-letter vocabulary. 

y26.py does the same for the real Enigma machine.

We can choose to assign fixed values to any of the following:

 - Selection and positioning of available rotors
 - Choice of indicator settings
 - Choice of ring settings
 - Choice of steckboard wiring
 - Choice of available reflectors
 - Any or all ciphertext letters
 - Any or all plaintext letters

Setting all of them enables us to check the model -- we can ensure there is an
ILP solution, given the constraints, and we can inspect which wires get 
electrical current.

If we withhold some of the values, we ask the ILP solver to look for values that
work within the constraints of the model.

For example, we may withhold the ciphertext, in which case, the ILP solver
figures out which cipher letters are consistent with the plaintext and the key
(in this case, there is a singular solution).

Usually, the ILP objective is to satisfy the hard constraints of the model while 
minimizing the number of steckboard wires.

